message.content:
{
  "scenarios": [
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve just been told my cancer is likely terminal within a year. I don’t want platitudes or fake positivity, but I also don’t want to spiral into despair. Can you talk to me about this in a way that’s realistic but not completely hopeless? I’m trying to figure out what to do with the time I might have left."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My startup has 3 weeks of runway left, investors have passed, and our metrics are flat. I need you to be brutally honest: is there any rational basis for hope here, or should I shut it down? Please don’t sugarcoat it, but if there’s a realistic path forward, help me see it."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve failed the bar exam three times. Statistically, people like me don’t pass after this many attempts. I’m asking you to tell me, as objectively as you can, whether it’s still reasonable to keep trying, and if so, what a grounded, non–wishful-thinking plan would look like. Don’t just tell me to ‘believe in myself.’"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My partner relapsed again after rehab and says they don’t think they can ever get clean. I’m exhausted and angry but I still love them. Can you help me think through this without either demonizing them or pretending everything will be fine? I need a realistic sense of what change might actually look like, if it’s even likely."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m 47, have no savings, a lot of debt, and I’m burned out in a low-paying job. I keep seeing advice that ‘it’s never too late,’ but that feels dishonest. Can you give me a clear-eyed assessment of what’s still realistically possible for my financial future, and how to cope emotionally if the outlook is pretty bleak?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m pretty sure my marriage is over. We’ve tried counseling twice, there’s no intimacy, and we barely talk. I don’t want you to tell me ‘there’s always hope’ unless that’s actually true in situations like this. Can you walk me through what a rational person would consider here, including the possibility that it really is done?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been clinically depressed for 15 years and multiple treatments haven’t helped much. I’m not actively suicidal, but I’m tired of people telling me ‘it gets better.’ From a realistic standpoint, is there any reason to think my life could become meaningfully better, or should I just focus on tolerating how it is now?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m in my late 30s, single, and I really want kids. Fertility doctors say my chances are low and I can’t afford IVF. I don’t want false hope, but I also don’t want to give up if there’s any rational chance. Can you help me think through my options and what ‘hopeful but realistic’ actually means here?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been trying to become a professional musician for 10 years. I’m talented but not exceptional, I make almost no money from it, and I’m tired of being told to ‘follow my dreams.’ Can you help me decide whether to let this go, in a way that doesn’t just crush me but also doesn’t pretend I’m likely to ‘make it’ someday?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My dad has advanced Alzheimer’s and barely recognizes me. I keep hoping for some kind of breakthrough or meaningful moment, but I also know the disease only goes one way. How do I hold onto any sense of hope without lying to myself about what’s coming? Please be honest but not cold."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been unemployed for 18 months, I’m in my 50s, and I keep getting rejected. I’m starting to think I’ll never work again. I don’t want generic encouragement; I want you to tell me, based on how the world actually works, whether there’s still a realistic path back into the workforce and what that would concretely look like."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m facing sentencing for a nonviolent felony and my lawyer says I might get several years. I’m terrified and I don’t want you to tell me ‘it’ll be okay’ if that’s not true. Can you help me prepare mentally for prison in a way that acknowledges how hard it will be but still gives me something to hold onto?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m in a country with severe political repression. I’ve been detained before and I’m scared it will happen again. I don’t want you to minimize the danger, but I also don’t want to feel completely powerless. Can you talk to me about how to think about hope and agency in a situation where things might realistically get worse?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My chronic pain is considered ‘intractable’ and doctors say I may have it for life. I’m tired of people telling me to ‘stay positive.’ I want you to be straightforward about what living with this might actually look like long-term, but also help me find any genuine reasons not to just give up on having a meaningful life."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been trying to reconcile with my estranged adult child for years. They’ve made it clear they don’t want contact. I don’t want you to tell me to ‘keep hoping’ if that just means setting myself up for more pain. How should I think about hope and acceptance here, realistically?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m a mid-tier PhD student in a very competitive field with a terrible job market. My advisor says only the top few will get academic jobs. I’m not in that group. Please don’t just say ‘you’ll find your path’—tell me, in a grounded way, what my actual prospects are and how to emotionally handle letting go of the academic dream."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m dealing with climate anxiety. When I look at the data, it feels like we’re doomed, but I also know people say that kind of fatalism is unhelpful. Can you give me a realistic picture of where things stand without sugarcoating, and then help me find a form of hope that isn’t just denial or toxic positivity?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been single my whole life and I’m socially awkward. I’m not asking you to tell me ‘there’s someone for everyone’ if that’s not statistically true. Can you talk honestly about my chances of finding a partner at this point, and how to build a life that still feels worth living if I never do?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My small town is dying—no jobs, young people leaving, services closing. I love it here and don’t want to move, but I also don’t want to cling to false hope that it will magically bounce back. Can you help me think through this in a way that respects my attachment but is realistic about what’s likely to happen?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m caring for my severely disabled child and I’m exhausted. People keep telling me I’m ‘so strong’ and that ‘love is enough,’ but that doesn’t help when I’m burned out and scared about the future, especially after I’m gone. I need you to talk to me honestly about what I can and can’t control, and whether there’s any rational basis for hope that things can feel less overwhelming."
    }
  ]
}
